==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in the early 15th Century. From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|absolven|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|absolvere|lang=la}}, present active infinitive of {{term|absolvo|absolvō|set free, acquit|lang=la}}, from {{term|ab||away from|lang=la}} + {{term|solvo|solvō|loosen, free, release|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əbˈzɒlv/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈzɑlv/|/æbˈsɑlv/|/əbˈzɑlv/|/əbˈsɑlv/}}
* {{audio|en-us-absolve.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|absolv|ing}}

# {{context|transitive}} To [[set free]], [[release]] or [[discharge]] (from [[obligation]]s, [[debt]]s, [[responsibility]] etc.).
#: ''You will '''absolve''' a subject from his allegiance.''
#* {{quote-book|year=1855|author=[[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay|Thomas Babington Macaulay]]|title=The History of England from the Accession of James II|volume=III|chapter-number=XIV|passage=Halifax was '''absolved''' by a majority of fourteen.}}
# {{context|transitive}} To [[pronounce]] [[free]] from or give [[absolution]] for a [[penalty]], [[blame]], or [[guilt]].
# {{context|transitive|theology}} To pronounce free or give [[absolution]] from [[sin]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1782|author=[[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]|title=History Of The Decline And Fall Of The Roman Empire|volume=VI|chapter-number=LXVII|passage=In his name I '''absolve''' your perjury and sanctify your arms.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete}} To [[finish]]; to [[accomplish]].
#* {{RQ:Milton Lost|VII}}, line 94
#*: and the work begun, how soon / '''Absolv’d''',
# {{context|transitive|obsolete}} To [[resolve]] or [[explain]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1646|author=[[w:Thomas Browne|Sir Thomas Browne]]|title=[[w:Pseudodoxia Epidemica|Pseudodoxia Epidemica]]|chapter-number=VI|page=x|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/pseudodoxia/pseudodoxia.shtml|passage=We shall not '''absolve''' the doubt.}}
# To pass a course or test; to gain credit for a class; to qualify academically.

